{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:44:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:44:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"58"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"58","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/58"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.03,0.46,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"58"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41201"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"58","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/58"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"58"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25935"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"3021"},{"type":"tags","id":"3337"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38404"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41201"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old at the end of her first year university studies attends her General Practice requesting help with her \u201cexam nerves\u201d. During examinations, most significantly OSCEs, she reports feeling faint and diaphoretic. She also feels nauseated and experiences palpitations and feels short of breath. She has sometimes felt numbness in her fingers. This has never previously been an issue for this patient, but has happened with increasing frequency over the last six months since receiving a poor examination mark earlier in the year. She has avoided two mid-term assessments since due to worry about these symptoms reoccurring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe reports that her overall mood is positive, which is congruent with her affect in the consultation, and that she is able to function well throughout the day and sleeps comfortably seven hours a night. She eats well and exercises three times a week. She has attended meditation classes and has tried \u201cpositive self-talking\u201d but does not feel that this has assisted her. She finds that she is preoccupied with thinking about these panic symptoms for the majority of the day in the lead up to her exams.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following diagnoses is the most consistent with her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Specific phobia","Adjustment disorder","Panic disorder","PTSD","Generalised anxiety disorder"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms that this patient is experiencing are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Especific phobia\u003C/strong\u003E disorder, in this case \u0027assessment\u0027 phobia. These attacks have become recurrent, however occur in predictable triggering situations surrounding assessment. The patient has experienced functional impairment now being unable to attend assessments, however this impairment only occurs in relation to upcoming exams. DSM-V criteria for specific phobias include the presence of unreasonable, excessive fear, avoidance or extreme distress, significant impact of life activities, lasting greater than 6 months and cannot be due to any underlying disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely as there is not clear onset stress event and the symptoms have been of likely gradual onset; further there is a focus surrounding panic attacks and this better explains the presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPanic disorder \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised not by just panic attacks (that occur in other anxiety and mood disorders) but also by their unexpected nature. They may be cued or triggered by certain circumstances (as in this case) but must always also be non-cued or unexpected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA diagnosis of PTSD requires many criteria to be met and follows after a significant, often life threatening event. This patient is not experiencing PTSD. While she did have a negative experience in a previous exam, this does not fit the criteria for a stressor as stated in the DSM-V. Further to this, other than avoidant features, the patient does not fit any of the other criteria that must be met for a diagnosis of PTSD to be given. These include: recurrent, involuntary, and intrusive distressing memories of the traumatic event(s), negative alterations in cognitions and mood associated with the traumatic event(s), marked alterations in arousal and reactivity with significant impact on the persons social and occupational life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct as the anxiety is specifically focussed to exam settings and not more widely occurring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Avoidant behaviours to a specific trigger which do not exist outside of this trigger are most likely to be due to Specific Phobias"],"references":["American Psychiatric Association: Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders: Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition. Arlington, VA: American Psychiatric Association, 2013."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25935"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"58"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25935"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-06T09:05:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T13:56:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"58"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41201"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1051","l